Problem Selection

In light of the time context of this assignment, the approaching end of the semester and finals period is the moment university and educational institutions send their students course evaluation forms to assess their feedback and experience from the courses they have taken within the semester.

Students answers from course evaluations yield crucial insights on receptivity to teaching practices, quality of the learning, and performance of professors. Thus, in this project, we decided to apply several machine learning models on a data set comprised of students course evaluation answers, compiled over the span of 5 year from the University of Queensland, Australia. Our first goal is to predict students overall course rating based on the different available features, while our second goal is to understand the relationship between the features and the response variable, by determining what factors influence students rating and thus the perceived quality of learning the most and by what extent.

While our analysis and results are adequate to Queensland university and its students, to a certain extent, the results of this work can be extended to the other institutions to tailor the educational experience of their students to their needs, and refine the strategies of course delivery for an enhanced student performance and quality of teaching at the university.

Dataset Selection

The dataset we have provided is a tabular representation of survey or assessment data. It comprises various columns, each offering insights into different aspects of the survey. These include mean scores (MeanQ1 to MeanQ8) for different questions, providing an overview of overall responses. The column AgreeQ8 was present but has been removed. The source of the dataset did not provide details of what the AgreeQ8 column represents and it seems that it has been generated for the purposes of their research, so we will not be considering it in our analysis.

Other key columns include:

TotalResponses: Reflects the total number of responses received for the survey or assessment.
Class_size: Indicates the size of the class or group participating in the survey.
ResponseRate: Represents the percentage of responses received out of the total potential responses.
Year and Semester: Provide information about when the survey was conducted.
Campus: Specifies the location or campus where the survey took place.
DeliveryMode: Distinguishes between internal and external survey delivery.
No_Academics: Appears to be associated with the number of academic staff or faculty
Prelude: A categorical variable, possibly related to the introductory section of the survey.
Rank and Gender: Include details about the rank and gender of the survey participants.

This dataset appears to cover multiple years, with responses from various campuses, delivery modes, and participant demographics

Exploring the colinearity of features

In order to select our most significant features, we want to explore the collinearity between our predictors. We generate a correlation matrix and plot it as a heat map as follows:

numeric_columns <- data %>% select_if(is.numeric)
corr_matrix <- cor(numeric_columns)
ggcorrplot(corr_matrix)

From the heat map, wee can deduce the following:

  • The 7 questions are highly collinear and positively correlated with one another. This can be explained by students enjoying multiple aspects of the course for a good experience, or disliking multiple aspects leading to a mediocre experience.

  • There is a collinearity between class Size and response Rate, which is expected since a bigger class size would lead to a higher number of response for a fixed response Rate.

  • We also notice that responseRate is positively correlated with the 7 questions, and a tad more correlated with the Received Feedback feature. This suggests that students are more likely to fill the evaluation form for a course they enjoyed, and especially for a course in which the professor was receptive to feedback. This is a valuable insight that we will further explore in our discussion.

Missing Values

Feature Engineering

Low Variance Features

Features with low variance are features that have little differences if at all in their values across the different observations in the data set. Because these features hold little discriminatory power, we can omit them to reduce our dimensional without losing crucial information. We chose our definition of low variance here to be the default values used by the caret library nearZeroVar function.

low_variance_features <- nearZeroVar(data)

low_variance_features
## integer(0)

None of the features has a variance near zero, thus we keep all the features for now.

Grouping features

Our prelude feature represents the course identifiers. However, we have 17 different course identifiers. This becomes bothersome once we encode them, because of high dimensionality. Instead, we will group course identifiers that fall within the same field to reduce our dimensions from 17 courses to 4 fields.

unique(data$Prelude)

## [16] STAT BOTN
## 17 Levels: AGRC ANIM BIOL BOTN CHEM ENVM FINM FOOD HORT IBUS LAND LPWM ... STAT

We group our courses into fields as follows:

  • Agricultural Sciences: AGRC, HORT, PLNT, FOOD

  • Animal Sciences: ANIM

  • Biological Sciences: BIOL, BOTN, MICR

  • Environmental Sciences: ENVM, LAND, LPWM

  • Business Management: FINM, IBUS, MGTS, MKTG

  • Chemistry and Mathematics: CHEM, STAT

course_to_field <- list(
  Agricultural_Sciences = c("AGRC", "HORT", "PLNT", "FOOD"),
  Animal_Sciences = c("ANIM"),
  Biological_Sciences = c("BIOL", "BOTN", "MICR"),
  Environmental_Sciences = c("ENVM", "LAND", "LPWM"),
  Business_Management = c("FINM", "IBUS", "MGTS", "MKTG"),
  Chemistry_Mathematics= c("CHEM", "STAT")
)

# Function to assign field based on course
get_field <- function(course) {
  for (field in names(course_to_field)) {
    if (course %in% unlist(course_to_field[field])) {
      return(field)
    }
  }
  return("Other")  # Default category if course doesn't match any rule
}

data$Field <- sapply(data$Prelude, get_field)
data$Field<-as.factor(data$Field)

Outliers

Outliers can negatively impact the performance of some machine learning algorithms. Removing or adjusting them can improve model robustness. In the previous data exploration we did, we noticed the presence of outliers in our numerical columns, so we are now going to remove them.

# Function to remove outliers based on IQR
remove_outliers <- function(x) {
  qnt <- quantile(x, c(0.05, 0.95), na.rm = TRUE)
  H <- 1.5 * IQR(x, na.rm = TRUE)
  x[(x < (qnt[1] - H)) | (x > (qnt[2] + H))] <- NA
  return(x)
}

# Apply the remove_outliers function to each numeric column
data[, numeric_columns] <- apply(data[, numeric_columns], 2, remove_outliers)

# Remove rows with any NA values (rows containing outliers)
data <- na.omit(data)

Tree-Based Methods

In this section, we leverage the caret package in R to develop and assess machine learning models for predicting the overallRating variable, with a specific emphasis on the role of decision trees in our approach. The ensemble comprises a foundational decision tree, a pruned decision tree achieved through parameter tuning, a random forest model, and a gradient boosting model utilizing a Gaussian distribution. Through a 5-fold cross-validation strategy, we systematically train and evaluate each model. Notably, decision trees play a pivotal role in our methodology, serving as the building blocks for the ensemble and providing interpretability to the overall predictive framework. Post-resampling analysis calculates the Mean Squared Error for individual models on an independent test dataset, enabling a focused evaluation of how decision trees contribute to the predictive accuracy of the ensemble within the context of our broader project.

suppressWarnings({
ctrl <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 5, summaryFunction = defaultSummary, classProbs = FALSE, verboseIter = FALSE,)

tree_model <- train(overallRating ~ ., data = train_data, method = "rpart", trControl = ctrl)

pruned_tree_model <- train(overallRating ~ ., data = train_data, method = "rpart", trControl = ctrl, tuneGrid = data.frame(cp = 0.01))

rf_model <- train(overallRating ~ ., data = train_data, method = "rf", trControl = ctrl)

gbm_model <- train(overallRating ~ ., data = train_data, method = "gbm", trControl = ctrl, verbose = FALSE, distribution = "gaussian",preProcess="zv")

# Suppressing warnings due to regression scenario where a good split might not be found,
# leading to the use of the average outcome as the predictor. In such cases,
# calculating R^2 is not feasible as the variance of the predictions is zero.

tree_performance <- postResample(pred = predict(tree_model, newdata = test_data), obs = test_data$overallRating)

pruned_tree_performance <- postResample(pred = predict(pruned_tree_model, newdata = test_data), obs = test_data$overallRating)

rf_performance <- postResample(pred = predict(rf_model, newdata = test_data), obs = test_data$overallRating)

gbm_performance <- postResample(pred = predict(gbm_model, newdata = test_data), obs = test_data$overallRating)

print(paste("Decision Tree MSE: ", mean(tree_performance^2,na.rm = TRUE)))
print(paste("Pruned Decision Tree MSE: ", mean(pruned_tree_performance^2,na.rm = TRUE)))
print(paste("Random Forest MSE: ", mean(rf_performance^2,na.rm = TRUE)))
print(paste("Gradient Boosting MSE: ", mean(gbm_performance^2,na.rm = TRUE)))
})
## [1] "Decision Tree MSE:  0.289420011125109"
## [1] "Pruned Decision Tree MSE:  0.298185379406018"
## [1] "Random Forest MSE:  0.318111597602254"
## [1] "Gradient Boosting MSE:  0.316841127346165"

Insights

  • Decision Tree MSE The basic decision tree demonstrates the lowest MSE among the models, suggesting a relatively strong predictive performance. However, its important to consider potential overfitting due to the simplicity of the model.

  • Pruned Decision Tree MSE The pruned decision tree exhibits a slightly higher MSE compared to the basic decision tree. While pruning is intended to enhance generalization, it appears to have a trade-off with predictive accuracy in this case.

  • Random Forest MSE The random forest model, despite its ensemble nature, shows a higher MSE than the decision tree models. This might be attributed to the complexity introduced by the ensemble, highlighting the need for further tuning.

  • Gradient Boosting MSE The gradient boosting model demonstrates a competitive MSE, similar to the random forest. Gradient boosting often performs well but requires careful tuning, and the choice of hyperparameters may impact its effectiveness.

Support Vector Machine

We are now going to train our SVM model. Since our output variable is a continuous numerical variable, the SVM will be a Support Vector Regressor. Support Vector Regression (SVR) works on similar principles as Support Vector Machine (SVM) classification.

The order of this section will be as follows: we are first going to run the SVM on different kernels (linear, polynomial and radial). We are also going to try different hyperparameters for each (like different degrees for polynomial, different cost value and different gamma values for radial kernel). We are then going to analyze our results and perform hyperparameter tuning to build the best model.

SVM with Linear kernel

The first kernel we will try is the linear kernel. The performance of this will tell us more about the distribution of our data and if we have a linear relationship. We will begin experimenting with a low cost value, along which we would expect the margin to be wide with many support vectors.

set.seed(123)
svm_model_linear <- svm(overallRating ~ ., data = train_data, kernel = "linear", cost = 1)

predictions <- predict(svm_model_linear, newdata = test_data)

mse_linear <- mean((test_data$overallRating - predictions)^2)
cat("Mean Squared Error:", mse_linear, "\n")
## Mean Squared Error: 0.04687832
r_squared_linear <- 1 - sum((test_data$overallRating - predictions)^2) / sum((test_data$overallRating - mean(test_data$overallRating))^2)
cat("R-squared:", r_squared_linear, "\n")
## R-squared: 0.9405035

The linear kernel gave us good results for both the MSE and R-squared.

We can obtain information about the SVM by building a summary as follows:

We can notice that, we can achieve the best linear kernel SVM model with cost of 0.1.

SVM with Radial kernel

The final kernel we will try is the radial kernel. We will initally start with cost of 1 and gamma 0.01 before trying other values.

set.seed(123)
svm_model_radial <- svm(overallRating ~ ., data = train_data, kernel = "radial", gamma = 0.01, cost = 1)

predictions <- predict(svm_model_radial, newdata = test_data)

mse_radial <- mean((test_data$overallRating - predictions)^2)
cat("Mean Squared Error:", mse_radial, "\n")
## Mean Squared Error: 0.05106622
r_squared_radial <- 1 - sum((test_data$overallRating - predictions)^2) / sum((test_data$overallRating - mean(test_data$overallRating))^2)
cat("R-squared:", r_squared_radial, "\n")
## R-squared: 0.9351883

This resulted in an R-squared better than the polynomial kernel but worse than the linear kernel. However this is not the best model we can get as we still did not tune the hyperparameters.

Let us run cross-validation on the gamma and cost hyperparameters.

set.seed(123)
tuning_grid <- expand.grid(gamma = c(0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 5, 10), cost = c(0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 10, 20, 30))

svm_tuned <- tune(svm, overallRating ~ ., data = train_data, kernel = "radial", ranges = tuning_grid)

best_model <- svm_tuned$best.model

predictions <- predict(best_model, newdata = test_data)

mse <- mean((test_data$overallRating - predictions)^2)
r_squared <- 1 - sum((test_data$overallRating - predictions)^2) / sum((test_data$overallRating - mean(test_data$overallRating))^2)

cat("Best Tuning Parameters: Gamma =", best_model$gamma, "and Cost =", best_model$cost, "\n")
## Best Tuning Parameters: Gamma = 0.001 and Cost = 10
cat("Mean Squared Error:", mse, "\n")
## Mean Squared Error: 0.0465061
cat("R-squared:", r_squared, "\n")
## R-squared: 0.9409759

Based on the cross-validation, the best gamma and cost values for the radial kernel are 0.001 and 10 respectively. With these values, we get better results than the polynomial and linear kernels, with the result being almost equal to that of the linear kernel but only very slightly higher. This tells us that the flexibility of the radial kernel was able to capture the data distribution properly. We also expect our data to be more linear in nature since the linear kernel was performing almost equally well.

SVM or Trees?

As we have seen, we achieved the best SVM model with radial kernel and it reached an MSE of 0.0465061. With the trees, our best performing model was the decision tree, with an MSE of 0.28942. When comparing the two models, we can conclude that the SVM outperforms the decision tree. This is expected since trees take the average of the different regions in a regression problem or might fail to find the best split.

Principle Component Analysis (PCA)

We use PCA as a dimensionality reduction technique to extract a new set of variable or principal components that will explain the variability of the data and the relationship with our response variable overallRating. PCA is relevant in our case because our data is multivariate with 13 features. PCA will help us reduce the dimensionality without losing information.

We start by excluding our categorical features and our response variable. We decided not to include the categorical features when performing PCA since it will likely not result in meaningful variance. This is because after one-hot encoding, our features have a covariance matrix with zero-off diagonal elements (the column values of a row will be mutually exclusive as only one of them can be 1).

Hence, the principal components will just be a rotation of the binary space and will not result in informative insights about patterns in the original categorical data.

conflicts_prefer(dplyr::select)
## [conflicted] Will prefer dplyr::select over any other package.
set.seed(123)
numeric_column_names<-c("clearUnderstanding","intellectuallySimulating","goodStructure","materialsUsefulness","clearRequirements","feedbackReceived","learningOutcome","TotalResponses","classSize","ResponseRate","Year", "Semester","noAcademics")
numeric_columns <- data %>% select(all_of(numeric_column_names))
corr_matrix <- cor(numeric_columns)
data.pca <- princomp(corr_matrix)
summary(data.pca)
## Importance of components:

Our PCA has generated 13 different components(since our maximum components is the number of numerical variables, which is 13). We are interested in looking at the values of each of Proportion of variance and Cumulative proportion.

Comp 1 has a proportion variance of 73.5%, which means that this component explain 73.5% of the variability in the data by itself. We see how other components have much smaller impacts on the variance. Naturally, the more components we add, the more our cumulative proportion increases, till reaching 100% by using all components.

Thus, we are interested in using as many components necessary as to decrease dimensionality, while explaining most of the variance.

We decide to keep Comp1 , Comp 2 with proportion variance of 73.5%, 10.9% respectively, as to achieve a cumulative proportion of 84% which we deem high enough.

In order to determine the number of clusters K, we will go for the elbow method. We will plot the Within Cluster Sum of Squares for multiple values of K, and determine the breaking point using the elbow method. The elbow is the point where the rate of decrease of the WCSS slows down.

wssplot <- function(data, nc, seed, line_color="blue"){
  wss <- (nrow(data)-1)*sum(apply(data, 2, var))
  for (i in 2:nc){
    set.seed(seed)
    wss[i] <- sum(kmeans(data, centers=i)$withinss)
  }
  plot(1:nc, wss, type = "b", xlab = "Number of Clusters", ylab = "Within Clusters Sum of Squares (WCSS)", col=line_color)
  # Add horizontal dashed lines at each data point on the y-axis
  for (i in 1:nc) {
    abline(h = wss[i], col = "gray", lty = 2)
  }
  wss
}
find_optimal_k <- function(wss_values) {
  # Calculate the second derivative of WSS
  wss_diff <- diff(diff(wss_values))
  print(wss_diff)
  # Find the index corresponding to the maximum second derivative
  elbow_index <- which.max(wss_diff) + 1
  
  # Return the optimal k
  optimal_k <- elbow_index + 1  # Adjust for 1-based indexing
  return(optimal_k)
}

wss_values <- wssplot(numerical_data, nc = 10, seed = 123)

wss_values

From the plotted graph,we can see that K= 2 and K=3 seems like good choices. On the other hand, from the result of calculating the elbow point using the second derivative, we get a value K=3. Lets explore hierarchical clustering and see what results it yields.

Hierarchal clustering

We will perform hierarchical clustering on different types of linkage, output our resulting dendograms and compare the results.

linkage_methods <- c("complete", "average","single", "centroid")
for (method in linkage_methods) {
 
  d <- dist(numerical_data, method = "euclidean")
  hc <- hclust(d, method = method)
  sub_grp <- cutree(hc, k = 2)

  plot(hc, main = paste("Linkage Method:", method), cex = 0.6, hang = -1)
  rect.hclust(hc, k = 2, border = 2:4)
  
}

fviz_nbclust(numerical_data, FUN = hcut, method = "silhouette")

As expected, we can see that our complete and average linkages produce evenly distributed clusters, compared to the single and centroid linkages. This is due to the nature of the different algorithms.

From the shape of the dendrograms, we can see that the clusters seem reasonably distinct at K=2. This aligns with our previous result from the elbow method in Kmeans. We also run a built-in fviz_nbclust function that gives us an approximation of the best K based on the silhouette method (The silhouette methods gives a measure of how similar an observation is to its cluster, versus how dissimilar it is from the other clusters).

As we are interested in the distribution of the features in these clusters, we plot a heat map that will showcase was each cluster includes.

d <- dist(numerical_data, method = "euclidian")
hc <- hclust(d, method = "complete")
sub_grp <- cutree(hc, k = 2)
clustered_data <- split(numerical_data, sub_grp)
cluster_means <- lapply(clustered_data, colMeans)
heatmap_data <- do.call(rbind, cluster_means)
heatmap(heatmap_data, main = "Feature Distribution Across Clusters", xlab = "Features", ylab = "Clusters")

The results of the heat map show that the observations were divided into two clusters which align with the groupings that we have seen so far in the data (the question responses are clustered, while other factors are clustered). However, it is more interesting to understand how observation are clstered based on the students assesment of the questions, rather than other objective course factors.

Thus, we repeat the same process but only include feature Q1 to Q7.

questions_column_names<-c("clearUnderstanding","intellectuallySimulating","goodStructure","materialsUsefulness","clearRequirements","feedbackReceived","learningOutcome")
questions_data<-data[,questions_column_names]
for (method in linkage_methods) {
 
  d <- dist(questions_data, method = "euclidean")
  hc <- hclust(d, method = method)
  sub_grp <- cutree(hc, k = 3)

  plot(hc, main = paste("Linkage Method:", method), cex = 0.6, hang = -1)
  rect.hclust(hc, k = 3, border = 2:4)
  
}

As we can see, the dendograms now display a different clustering, with K=3 looking like an optimal cut. We then proceed to graph our heat map base don that.

d <- dist(questions_data, method = "euclidian")
hc <- hclust(d, method = "complete")
sub_grp <- cutree(hc, k = 3)
clustered_data <- split(questions_data, sub_grp)
cluster_means <- lapply(clustered_data, colMeans)
heatmap_data <- do.call(rbind, cluster_means)
heatmap(heatmap_data, main = "Feature Distribution Across Clusters", xlab = "Features", ylab = "Clusters")

From this new heat map , we can extract the following insights: - It seems that students who had the best learning outcome were students who received the most helpful feedback on their performance throughout the course.

  • In Cluster two, we see that students who received the least feedback and had the least perceived learning were those who had the best understanding of the course outcomes, and found the course relatively intellectually stimulating. However, the low learning outcome of the class hints at the possibility that clear requirements isnt enough if not accompanied by a good learning environment.

  • Finally, it seems that an intellectually stimulating course material favorites the learning outcome of students. Future course development may incorporate intellectually stimulating components. However, more data is needed to identify what exactly makes a course intellectually stimulating.

Conclusion

In this report, we used a dataset of course evaluations compiled over multiple years from the University of Queensland, Australia. Touching upon the goals identified earlier in the problem selection, our findings were as follows:

  • SVM Model with radial kernel, gamma of 0.001 and cost of 10 resulted in the best prediction model when compared to different tree models.

  • The factors involved in the class environment and teaching method are much more relevant to the overall course rating compared to more objective factors like the class size, campus, gender, etc.

Future work includes collecting more data about the details of the learning environment like activities, projects and other coursework that will help us identify which of these components resulted in factors such as clear understanding, intellectually simulating.. etc which were related with higher ratings.
